    "contents" : "\\chapter{Chebychev's Theorem}\n\\label{Chebychev}\n\t\\markboth{Chebychev's}{Probability Distributions and Theory}\n\n%New Section\n\\section{Chebychev's Theorem}\n\\label{Chebychev1}\nIn any finite set of numbers and for any real number $h > 1$, at least $(1 - \\frac{1}{h^2}) \\cdot 100\\%$ of the numbers lie within $h$ standard deviations of the mean.  In other words, they lie within the interval $(\\mu-h\\cdot\\sigma , \\mu+h\\cdot\\sigma)$.\\\\\n\\\\\n\\it Proof: \\rm\\\\\n\\\\\nFor a set $\\{x_1,x_2,\\ldots,x_r,x_{r+1},\\ldots,x_n\\}$ where, by choice of labeling, $\\{x_1,x_2,\\ldots,x_r\\}$ lie outside of \n$(\\mu-h\\cdot\\sigma , \\mu+h\\cdot\\sigma)$.  Also, $\\{x_{r+1},\\ldots,x_n\\}$ are within the interval.  Under these conditions we know\\\\\n\\\\\n$|x_1-\\mu| > h\\sigma,\\ |x_2-\\mu| > h\\sigma, \\ldots,\\ |x_r-\\mu| > h\\sigma$.\\\\\nSquaring gives\\\\\n\\\\\n$(x_1-\\mu)^2 > h^2\\sigma^2,\\ (x_2-\\mu)^2 > h^2\\sigma^2,\\ldots,\\ (x_r-\\mu)^2 > h^2\\sigma^2\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow\\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{r}(x_1-\\mu)^2\n\t> \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{r}h^2\\sigma^2\n\t= rh^2\\sigma^2$.\\\\\nSince all $(x_i-\\mu)^2$ must necessarily be positive,\\\\\n\\\\\n$\\displaystyle \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{r}(x_i-\\mu)^2 < \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{n}(x_i-\\mu)^2\n\\indent\\Rightarrow rh^2\\sigma^2 < \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{n}(x_i-\\mu)^2\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow\\footnote[1]{$\\sigma^2 = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{n}(x_i-\\mu)^2\n\t\t\\Rightarrow n\\sigma^2 = \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{n}(x_i-\\mu)^2$}\n\t\\ \\ rh^2\\sigma^2 < n\\sigma^2\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow rh^2 < n\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow\\frac{r}{n} < \\frac{1}{h^2}$\n\\pagebreak\nand $\\frac{r}{n}$ is the fraction of numbers outside $(\\mu-h\\cdot\\sigma , \\mu+h\\cdot\\sigma)$.  By the law of complements, the fraction of numbers inside the interval is $1 - \\frac{r}{n}$, which implies $1 - \\frac{r}{n} > 1 - \\frac{1}{h^2}$.  Thus, more than $(1-\\frac{1}{h^2})\\cdot 100\\%$ of the points lie within $h$ standard deviations of the mean, or within the interval $(\\mu-h\\cdot\\sigma , \\mu+h\\cdot\\sigma)$. \\rule{.05in}{.05in}\n\n%New Section\n\\section{Alternate Proof of Chebychev's Theorem}\n\\label{Chebychev2}\nIn any finite set of numbers and for any real number $h>1$, at least $(1-\\frac{1}{h^2})\\cdot 100\\%$ of the numbers lie within $h$ standard deviations of the mean.  In other words, they lie within the interval $(\\mu-h\\cdot\\sigma,\\mu+h\\cdot\\sigma)$.\\\\\n\\\\\n\\it Proof: \\rm \\\\\n\\\\\nThe proof here is done for the discrete case, but is applicable also in the continuous case by replacing the summations with integrals (with integrals, the limits will be from $-\\infty$ to $\\infty$).\\\\\n$\\displaystyle \\sigma^2\n\t= E(x-\\mu)^2\n\t= \\sum\\limits_{y=0}^{\\infty}(y-\\mu)^2p(y)\\\\\n\\indent\t= \\sum\\limits_{y=0}^{\\mu-h\\sigma}(y-\\mu)^2p(y) + \\sum\\limits_{y=\\mu-h\\sigma+1}^{\\mu+h\\sigma-1}(y-\\mu)^2p(y)\n\t\t+ \\sum\\limits_{y=\\mu+h\\sigma}^{\\infty}(y-\\mu)^2p(y)\\\\\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow\\footnote[1]{since all the $(y-\\mu)^2$ must be positive, removing the middle term will surely result in this inequality.}\n\t\\ \\ \\sigma^2\\geq \\sum\\limits_{y=0}^{\\mu-h\\sigma}(y-\\mu)^2p(y)\n\t\t+ \\sum\\limits_{y=\\mu+h\\sigma}^{\\infty}(y-\\mu)^2p(y)\\\\$\n\\\\\nIn both of these summations $y$ is outside the interval $(\\mu-h\\cdot\\sigma , \\mu+h\\cdot\\sigma)$, so $|y-\\mu| \\geq h\\sigma \n\t\\Rightarrow (y-\\mu^2) \\geq h^2\\sigma^2$.\\\\\n\\\\\n$\\displaystyle\\indent\\Rightarrow \\sigma^2 \\geq \\sum\\limits_{y=0}^{\\mu-h\\sigma}h^2\\sigma^2p(y)\n\t\t+ \\sum\\limits_{\\mu+h\\sigma}^{\\infty}h^2\\sigma^2p(y)\\\\\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow\\sigma^2\\geq h^2\\sigma^2\\Big[\\sum\\limits_{y=0}^{\\mu-h\\sigma}p(y)\n\t\t+ \\sum\\limits_{\\mu+h\\sigma}^{\\infty}p(y)\\Big]\\\\$\n\\\\\nThe first summation is the sum of all probabilities that $y-\\mu < h\\sigma$, i.e. $P(y-\\mu < h\\sigma)$.  \nLikewise, the second summation is $P(y-\\mu > h\\sigma)$.\\\\\n\\\\\n$\\displaystyle \\indent\\Rightarrow\\sigma^2 \\geq h^2\\sigma^2[P(y-\\mu<h\\sigma) + P(y-\\mu>h\\sigma)]\\\\\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow \\sigma^2 \\geq h^2\\sigma^2[P(|y-\\mu|>h\\sigma)]\\\\\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{h^2} \\geq P(|y-\\mu|>h\\sigma)\\\\\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow 1-\\frac{1}{h^2} \\leq P(|y-\\mu|>h\\sigma)$\\ \\rule{.05in}{.05in}\n\n\n%New Section\n\\section{Chebychev's Theorem for Absolute Deviation}\n\\label{Chebychev3}\nThis theorem is provided by Brunette \\cite{Brunetb}\\\\\n\\\\\nIn any finite set of numbers, and for any real number $h > 1$, at least $1 - \\frac{1}{h}$ of the numbers lie within $h$ absolute deviations of the mean, where the absolute deviation is defined $Ab = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum\\limits_{i=1}{n}|x_i-\\bar x|$.  In other words, $1-\\frac{1}{h}$ of the numbers are in the interval $(\\bar x-h\\cdot Ab , \\bar x+h\\cdot Ab)$.\\\\\n\\\\\n\\it Proof: \\rm \\\\\n\\\\\nFor a set $\\{x_1,x_2,\\ldots,x_r,x_{r+1},\\ldots,x_n\\}$ where, by choice of labeling, $\\{x_1,x_2,\\ldots,x_r\\}$ lie outside of \n$(\\mu-h\\cdot Ab , \\mu+h\\cdot Ab)$.  Also, $\\{x_{r+1},\\ldots,x_n\\}$ are within the interval.  Accordingly,\\\\\n\\\\\n$\\displaystyle h \\cdot Ab \\leq |x_1-\\bar x| ,\\ h \\cdot Ab \\leq |x_1-\\bar x| ,\\ldots ,\\ h \\cdot Ab \\leq |x_1-\\bar x|\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow r \\cdot h \\cdot Ab \\leq \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{r}|x_i-\\bar x|\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow r \\cdot h \\cdot Ab \\leq \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{n}|x_i-\\bar x|\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow\\footnote[2]{$Ab = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{n}|x_i-\\bar x|\n\t\t\\Rightarrow n \\cdot Ab = \\sum\\limits_{i=1}^{n}|x_i-\\bar x|$ }\n\t\\ \\ r \\cdot h \\cdot Ab \\leq n \\cdot Ab\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow \\frac{r}{n} \\leq \\frac{1}{h}\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow -\\frac{r}{n} \\geq -\\frac{1}{h}\\\\\n\\indent\\Rightarrow 1-\\frac{r}{n} \\geq 1-\\frac{1}{h}$.\\\\\n\\\\\nNow $\\frac{r}{n}$ is the fraction of numbers outside the interval.  So $1-\\frac{r}{n}$ is the fraction of numbers within $h$ absolute deviations of the mean, or within the interval $(\\mu-h\\cdot Ab , \\mu+h\\cdot Ab)$.\\rule{.05in}{.05in}\n\n",
